	<h3>The Charming Bard</h3>
	
	<h4>Charm Introduction</h4>
      <P>
	Charm kiting is a crucial survival tactic for both a grouping bard, and especially a soloing bard. Once you've tasted the success of Charm, you will always want to have it memmed.
	<br><br>
	<b>Solon's Song of the Sirens (27)</b><br>
	Bards receive their first Charm song at level 27 - <A target=_new href="/songs.asp?song=28">Solon's Song of the Sirens</A>. This song will only work on mobs that are level 37 or below. You may easily use this song up until you get your upgrade charm song, and even then, I am still using this song sometimes.
	<br><br>
	<b>Solon's Bewitching Bravura (39)</b><br>
	At level 39, you will receive your next Charm song upgrade - <A target=_new href="/songs.asp?song=41">Solon's Bewitching Bravura</A>. This song charms target up to 18 seconds and also lowers their magic resistance (enhanced by using a wind instrument). It is such a powerful song at a bard's disposal, that is required 20 mana, which can go down pretty quickly actually. This Charm song upgrade only works on mobs below level 55. When you first get this song, you will get the usual resists alot, and your mana will go down quickly so don't be afraid to swap it out for your level 27 Charm song, it will still work on the blue mobs you are fighting.
	<br><br>
	<b>Charming a mob</b><br>
	If you have been an enchanter or druid in a previous life, our charm songs are similar to their Charm spells, where you "recruit" the help of a nearby mob. The sole difference is that our charm song only lasts less than 15 seconds (typically 12 seconds), rather than 8 minutes. During this time, you can turn a mob into your pet who is at your beck and call. Sic him onto his friends and watch the fun. When the charm breaks, the pet will be very aggro on you, so be sure to be prepared on what to do next. After reading this charm guide, you will have a pretty good idea what you should do next.
	<br><br>
	<b>Charmed with Charm!</b><br> 
	Why do bards love charm so much? Its simple. For 
      soloing bards, it gives you the freedom to solo safely and easily, and 
      with no downtime. You may take on mobs that are yellow and white to you in 
      relative safety. For grouping bards, it allows you to turn the tables in a 
      fight, and pit one mob against the other, while the tanks are focusing on 
      another mob, making it a good crowd control tactic. If you are the party's 
      designated puller and need to pull a casting mob, sometimes the mob likes 
      to stand back and nuke you. With charm, the mob's nukes will bounce off of 
      you (since you are on their side now), and you can also command the mob to 
      follow you back to your party. Much easier than without charm! </P>
      <P> 
	                                                          Lastly, if you're in a group and a group member is getting aggroed on, charm the mob, its a very powerful way to taunt the mob off when all else fails. It has saved the life of many of my past group members. For this reason, I often have charmed mem even with a chanter in the party... Its that powerful. Thus, charm is one of the best songs a bard can have.  So read on, and turn yourself into a Charming Bard...
	<br><br><br><br></P>
	<hr>
	<h4>Factors of Charm Success</h4>
	Before we start with the heart of this guide, it is actually more important to be prepared. I've dedicated a large percentage of this guide to preparing a Bard to achieve success with charm. Almost all of these preparations are in your control.
	<br><br>
	Many bards try out their charm songs and get frustrated right away, and end up never using charm. I will do my best to guide you on how to use charm successfully to your advantage. There are many factors to your Charming Success.<br><br>
	<b>Charm Success Factors:</b><BR>
	<ol>
	<li><b>Charisma</b>
	<li><b>Knowing the Pet Commands</b>
	<li><b>Good Charm setup</b>
	<li><b>The right environment/mob</b>
	<li><b>Decent Internet Connection</b>
	<li><b>Good Group Communication (if using charm while grouping)</b>
	<li><b>ALOT OF PRACTICE</b></li>
	</ol>
	All of these factors are crucial to your Charming success. If you have a problem with just one of these factors, you might not have the best of luck with charm. I will now go into each of these factors in a bit more detail...
	<br><br><br><br>
	<hr>
	<h4>Charisma</h4>
	Charm songs have their resistance check based on your charisma, the mobs magic resistance, and the level of the mob compared to you. Aside from selecting the appropriate mob to charm, you can increase the odds for a successful and longer lasting charm with your charisma.
	<br>
	<b>Increasing your charisma</b><br>
	If you haven't concentrated on increasing your charisma yet, you should now. If it is too low, look into increasing it. Many bards say they are just fine with 112 charisma, while others have 150 charisma or higher. A guideline should be to try and get it above 120 charisma if you intend to do charm and crowd control alot. If you can go higher, all the better!
	<br><br>
	<b>Charisma-enhancing Items</b><br>
	Some items that will increase a bards charm include: 
	<ul>
	<li>Star Ruby Veil (silver, platinum, velium) - (+5, +9, +10 cha respectively)
	<li>Electrum Star Ruby Rings (+7 cha each, +14 cha for pair)
	<li>Golden Cat's Eye Agate bracers (+7 cha each, +14 cha for pair)
	<li>Bard Illusion Masks (generally +13 cha)
	<li>Opalline Earrings (+5 cha each, +10 cha for pair)
	<li>Crude Stein (+15 cha)
	<li>Split Paw tooch necklace (+5 cha)
	<li>Laced Veil (+8 cha)
	<li>Lambent, Melodic, Resonant, Imbrued bard armor give charisma, depending on what level you can get this armor
	<li>Drake-hide Leggings (+5 cha)
	<li>Leatherfoot Raider's skullcap (+10 cha)
	<li>Singing Short Sword (+15 cha)
	<li>Harmonic Spear (+5 cha)
	<li>Symphonic Saber (+10 cha)
	<li>Sionachies Partisan (+6 cha)
	<li>Gleaming Short Sword (+5 cha)
	<li>Many of our higher level instruments add +15 
        cha</li>        
