	<h4>Prime Charm Environment/Mob</h4>
	<b>Prime charm environment</b><br> 
	The prime charm-kiting environment is one with wide open spaces for a bard to run around in, and plenty of mobs around your level. A bard with Selos and magical drum can easily outrun and lose their kited mobs, so be careful. Request a sow from a friendly druid or shaman, and then you don't have to worry about refreshing your sow every few seconds. Hilly or mountainous terrain may be difficult to run around for you, so find a zone with large, flat, open space where its easy to see.
	<br><br>
	<b>Charm-kiting zones</b><br> 
	Refer 
      to the Bard Hunting guide, many bards have told us their favorite charm-kiting territory. Some popular places to solo and charm-kite include: Lake of Ill Omen, The Overthere, Dreadlands, Burning Woods, Rathe Mountains, the Karanas, Iceclad Ocean, Eastern Wastelands...  For me, the grouping bard, Charm can come in handy in every single zone I play in. When you're grouped with others, your party can take on multiple mobs, you can charm one to attack another. Then, either join in on the fighting or buffing, or stand back a safe distance to be ready to charm again.
	<br><br>
	<b>Charming mobs</b><br>
	As for your charmed victims... Select the right mobs, this may be some trial and error at first. All mobs are different, some run slow, some some fast. Some have low magic resistance, some have high MR. Some are smart, some are dumb. Bards have most success pitting two different creatures against each other.
	<br><br><br><br>
	<hr>
	<h4>Decent Internet Connection</h4>
	Unfortunately, this factor does not fall into your control. If you have a 14.4 modem or just a plain bad Internet connection, charm may not be a viable strategy for you. Try it, and if it doesn't pan out well, you may look into getting a faster Internet connection. DSL or a cable modem might cost twice as much as a dial-up connection, but its worth every single penny.
	<br><br>
	<b>Bad Connection = Lag = Death</b><br>
	If your Internet connection fails you many times, it may be too dangerous to charm-kite. I have a cable modem, so I do not experience this too often, but there are days when my connection is bad too. When the connection bar turns red, you may opt to just start running to a safe place. When your connection goes bad, you have no control, but to wait it out. Whether you go Linkdead, or you come to within a moment, it is a bit of a risk. As a bard, you probably already have an idea of how good of a connection you have, the better the connection, the easier it makes a bard's life with both twisting and charming. I've heard a few bard tales of waking up after going Linkdead back in their bind spot naked.
	<br><br>
	<b>Your Computer</b><br>
	If you are serious about the game, it wouldn't hurt to make sure you have a computer that can keep up with you. Some things you can do to improve your game would be to get a faster processor, a good video card, and definitely more RAM. I would suggest investing in more RAM if you only have 64MB right now.
